##Intro##

How to get a job coding?

The purpose of this article is not to discuss the entire development ecosystem. My purpose is just to get you started on the journey as soon as possible. With that, nothing great in life is easy; so even if you don&#39;t belief or agree with what I have to say at least consider the suggestions. With that, I am NOT a coding master or even claim to be. This is just my, and many others, journey.

&nbsp;

####Who Am I?####

Well if you&#39;re on my personal blog I assume you at least have a general idea of who I am, so I&#39;ll keep it brief:

I started coding about 3.5 years ago, became obsessed, and am now a senior developer; I give talks at various meet up groups and help on a bunch of side projects. All of this came with a **TON** of work; coding on the weekends, working two full time jobs at once, taking near 500 hours of online classes, joining and speaking at various meetup groups, teaching, and volunteer coding projects.

Coding for me has been an obsessive enjoyable journey, like always trying to solve the puzzle. But that said, I&#39;m sure you can get good without being obsessed and in a slower more incremental manner.

My goal of this article is to get you started.

&nbsp;

##First Steps##

The first step is to learn the basics.

No matter what new framework or tool is on the market, they were all build on top of basic technologies.

I&#39;m not going heavily into technologies, but I will briefly overview different starting points:  
  
&nbsp;

1. Go to school for a bachelor&#39;s degree in Computer Science:
    * After or during school you&#39;ll get an internship.
    * The internship will _most likely_ teach you Back-End to Front-End development_._
    * Afterwards, you&#39;ll get a job and learn more Back-End systems and specialize or learn Front-End and go full stack. (wild over-simplification)
    * Keep learning and advancing into what you like doing.  

    &nbsp;

2. You didn&#39;t go to school for Computer Science but want to get into coding:
    * You&#39;ll start with a bootcamp or teaching yourself on your own.
    * ???
    * Profit

    &nbsp;

For the rest of this article we will be talking about option 2.

The reason is firstly because that&#39;s the route I chose and secondly, because it&#39;s probably the most applicable.

Front-End development has a much shorter time to first job and you can get a work at multiple levels along the learning process.

&nbsp;

##Pre-work##

If you don&#39;t know how to code, you won&#39;t get hired, pretty self-explanatory.

Your first thought might be to take an in-person bootcamp. I, however, couldn&#39;t afford the $10-20k sticker price on most in-person bootcamps.

So, I went to Udemy and bought one for $10.

This one, to be specific (I am not being paid for this recommendation).


 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

[https://www.udemy.com/course/the-web-developer-bootcamp/](https://www.udemy.com/course/the-web-developer-bootcamp/)

&nbsp;

Regardless of what beginning class you end up choosing, I would **HIGHY** recommend talking a cheap online class instead of an expensive bootcamp.

_Why?_

Because I do a lot of speaking at meet up groups, and the number 1 question I&#39;m asked is &quot;how to get a job?&quot;; mostly from people who just graduated an expensive bootcamp.

Which is disheartening to see.

In some case&#39;s the bootcamps will help you find work, but from what I&#39;ve seen, they aren&#39;t doing enough to justify the price.

&nbsp;


####Want to know the REAL secret to getting work as a web developer?####

Just pay $14.95 and the secret will be yours! Just kiddingâ€¦


The secret is simple but also frustrating; to get work as a developer, **you have to have work experience.**

Graduating a bootcamp is **not** enough.

&nbsp;


####To be clear:####

* Recruiters and hiring managers don&#39;t care what bootcamp you went to. Most won&#39;t even ask.
* Technical interviewers might ask if you&#39;re self-taught or went to a bootcamp, but don't really care either.

Save the money.

&nbsp;

So, what are the top factors in finding a job?

* **Work Experience**
* Online portfolio
* Education

&nbsp;


To help I&#39;ll break this up into 3 sections:

* Finding a job,
* Getting the job,
* Building your career.

&nbsp;

##Finding your first job:##

Going back to my last point, work experience is the **MOST** important factor in getting future work. And I&#39;ve seen countless applications shot down because of this.

Why would a company risk hiring someone who doesn&#39;t know if they like working with code? Development as a hobby is very different than working in it. 

Not to mention things untaught in bootcamps; like agile, scrum, slack, proper git pipelining, and so on. Things companies don&#39;t want to provide training for.

&nbsp;

####Well what should you do?####

1. **Drop your ego.**
    * You have no chance at immediately getting your dream job.
    * Take **ANY** job you can find.
    * Without work experience, you are close to worthless. Embrace that and act accordingly.



2. **Plan to put the work in:**
    * It&#39;s perfectly fine to work for free for the first 3 months; after that leave or ask for pay.
    * **ALWAYS** keep looking for new work. I love my current job; but my LinkedIn is always active, have a bunch of recruiters I can call at a moment&#39;s notice and am always applying to freelancing work.
    * Keep an upgrade timeline; at 3 months I&#39;m a Junior, 6 months Mid-level, 2 years senior and so on.



3. **Zero work experience is coal, one year+ is diamonds.**
    * Think of your first couple jobs as an investment into your future.



4. **Keep Networking!**
    * Go to Meetup groups, talk with recruiters, tech events. You&#39;ll not only help your job hunt, but also learn different technologies and meet lots of great people.



5. **Standard job-hunting practices apply:**
    * Keep a well-made resume. Here is a copy of mine: 
[https://www.kyleacannon.com/about/](https://www.kyleacannon.com/about/)
    * Apply to everything you see. Do it every day. Ask friends, neighbors.
    * Reach out to both recruiters and companies.

&nbsp;

If you do all of this you&#39;ll sooner or later get invited to interview for a job.

The **WORST** thing you can do is wait for a job you think you &quot;_deserve_&quot;, which was most of the people asking me how to find a job.


And these conversations went something like this:

_&quot;How can I get a job at XYZ?&quot;_

_&quot;Where are you working now?&quot;_

_&quot;I just graduated from a bootcamp&quot;_

_&quot;Oh, then it&#39;s going to be very difficultâ€¦ you&#39;re better off getting a different job and applying in a couple months&quot;_

_&quot;yeah butâ€¦ (doesn&#39;t listen to me)&quot;_


&nbsp;


##Getting your first job:##

This really depends on what level you&#39;re applying for. A senior position will require a lot more technical analysis than someone just starting.

&nbsp;

####But there are some universal principals that apply regardless:####

1. **Dress well** â€“ If meeting in person, dress accordingly. So many developers show up to interviews looking like slobs and wonder why they can&#39;t get a job.

2. **Be optimistic** â€“ A previous company I worked for posted a criteria checklist of what they wanted in a new React developer, and this is a true story;
    * Needs to know HTML/CSS/JS
    * Needs to be friendly
    * React is a plus.
(The core technology of the job was a _PLUS!_ Being friendly was more important than knowing the job, but obviously less than knowing the basics).

3. **Study &quot;Interview Questions&quot;** â€“ Interviewing in web development is different than the actual work. Interviewers will sometimes ask stupid and irrelevant questions. Mainly because they were upgraded to this role from a senior role and don&#39;t know how to interview.
So this unfortunate practice still takes place and you should study interview questions just in case.

&nbsp;


In general, I&#39;ll ask underlying knowledge questions. So, if it&#39;s a JavaScript related position, I might ask about object inheritance. Because if the developer doesn&#39;t understand inheritance, it&#39;s not going to work.

For CSS, I might ask about selector specificity or HTML I might ask about semantics and accessibility.

What is the underlying core importance of that piece of technology?

The latest features and tricks can always be taught; but if you don&#39;t understand the basics, it&#39;s a hopeless hire.

The other thing I watch out for are applicates who know everything and are difficult to have a conversation with. I might have to spend every day working with this person, why would I recommend someone I can&#39;t have 20 minute a phone call with?

A major part of the job is working with people.


Start thinking as if you are the interviewer, what type of person would **YOU** hire? Make it easy for them. They don&#39;t want to interview people either, and are rooting for you just as much as you are.

&nbsp;


##Building Your Career:##

Finally, you got the job! It probably won&#39;t be the best role, so we&#39;ll make a plan for the future.

&nbsp;

####If you&#39;re going Front-End, a possible career path could look like this:####

1. **HTML / CSS template designer: (Honestly should look for a position like this WHILE in school)**   
**[Free - $15/hr.: 0 â€“ 6 months]**  

    Basically builds HTML / CSS templates at a cheap rate for lazy developers who don&#39;t feel like doing it.

    **Important things to note** â€“ Responsiveness, accessibility, semantic HTML.
    Still a difficult job, especially if you&#39;re just starting out. But focusing 100% on HTML/CSS will greatly help you master each piece before moving forward. 

&nbsp;

2. **Junior UI Developer:**  
    **[$15-$30/hr.: 6 months â€“ 1 year]**

    Prettying much the same as above except you&#39;ll be expected to know some JavaScript.

    **Important things to note** â€“ DOM events, basic JavaScript functions, how browsers work.
    Browsers are incredibility complicated and take a while to learn.

    JavaScript has dozens of traps that can easily trick new developers. The best bet is to dive in fully as soon as possible. _I&#39;ll provide resources below._

&nbsp;

3. **UI Developer: (React or Vue)** 
    **[$30-50/hr.: 1 â€“ 3 years]**

    This is a big jump in learning, and you&#39;ll have to pick and choose a bit on what framework you want to learn. But regardless, you&#39;ll need to be an expert at JavaScript first.

    **Important things to note** â€“ React is the most popular and in my opinion, the most important. But even with react there are a ton of other libraries and frameworks you are expected to additionally know if you "_know react_".  
    But the same concepts apply. Learn from inside out. Most interviewers will forgive if you&#39;ve never used the latest features; but if you don&#39;t know how the virtual DOM works, it&#39;s game over.

&nbsp;

4. **Senior Developer: (React or Vue)** 
    **[$50+/hr.: 3 years +]**

    This usually requires Full Stack development; expected to know Node, Docker, cloud architecture, how to hire and train other developers, and much moreâ€¦

    **Note** â€“ Keep in mind, this is going the Front-End to Full Stack path. But there are many different senior positions and paths to follow.

There&#39;s also a great article on the technical aspects of this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

[https://levelup.gitconnected.com/the-2020-web-developer-roadmap-76503ddfb327](https://levelup.gitconnected.com/the-2020-web-developer-roadmap-76503ddfb327)


&nbsp;

##In conclusion:##

I hope this article helped illustrate a possible path into web development. I used the provided path as an example not just from my journey, but for almost every developer I&#39;ve met without a BS in Computer Science.

Some of whom, didn&#39;t go to college at all and are in the same or higher positions than I am.

&nbsp;


####Key Takeaways:####

1. Take a cheap online bootcamp and start applying to jobs as soon as you start.
2. Take whatever job you can get regardless of the pay.
3. Don&#39;t expect to be a master overnight. There&#39;s a tremendous amount of information to learn, and each piece should be fully understood before moving on.
4. Keep moving. If you stay at the HTML/CSS template job, you&#39;ll never learn JavaScript and so on.
5. Network before, during, and after your job hunt.
6. Development jobs are like all jobs; learn basic communication skills, make a nice resume, and be well groomed.
7. Finally, make sure to work hard so your employer is happy they hired you. It&#39;s just a contract after all, and both parties should leave happy.
